%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{[[is_prime]]}
\begin{itemize}
\item Now let's write a basic loop to check if this number [[n]] is a prime number.
\item We can do this by considering numbers in a certain range. If any of the
      numbers being considered are factors of [[n]], [[n]] is not prime.
\item Let's set the interval between numbers to $2$ since we don't need to consider
      even numbers. This means [[start]] needs to be odd.
\end{itemize}

<<Loop to check if prime>>=
  for i in range(start, end, 2):
    if n % i is 0:
      return False
    return True
@

\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{frame}[fragile]{[[is_prime]]}
\begin{itemize}
\item We can be smart about the checking for factors by defining a good range.
\item Obviously, the starting number cannot be smaller than $2$, since we already
      check if a number is divisible by 2. Let's set [[start]] to $3$.
\end{itemize}

<<Prepare loop to check if prime>>=
  start = 3
@

\begin{itemize}
\item We can set the end of the range to be [[n]] itself, but we should only check
      for one of the factors not both.
\item We do this by taking $\sqrt{n}$, then rounding down.
\item This requires the [[math]] package.
\end{itemize}

<<Prepare loop to check if prime>>=
  end = int(math.floor(math.sqrt(n)))
@

